What is your overall assessment of this course?
Do you expect to use this class for credit toward your major, or toward a pre-professional program?

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: You have to do it, and you will have a completely unique experience to anyone who came before you. So why are you reading this review?
This is research for credit within the BME major. You have to work on average 10 hours a week and make a 15 minute presentation (or write a 10 page paper) at the end of the semester.

Research for credit. Pick a project, like it, hope that you have enough data in the end to make it seem like you got something done. Don't worry, in most cases, everyone gets about 1/5 of the data they were expecting. Still- easy A, if you put in a reasonable amount of work.

I would highly encourage doing research for credit before your senior year. I learned a ton this semester since I spent a fair amount of time in lab, and I have a good idea of where my senior project will go next year. I benefitted from having a great mentor and PI who took the time to answer my questions and teach me as someone still relatively new to research. I cannot say enough great things of my time in the Miller-Jensen lab!

I would recommend BENG 472 as an excellent course for any student interested in biomedical engineering research. It is a requirement for seniors in the major during the second semester as a means to fulfill the senior project requirement. The course allows for a unique opportunity to conduct meaningful, cutting-edge research and work with renown faculty and researchers.
